                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d163">
                <head>163. Memorandum of a Conversation Between the Secretary of State and Senator
                        <persName>William F. Knowland</persName>, Washington, May 28, 1957<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d163fn1">Source: Eisenhower Library, Dulles
                        Papers, General Memoranda of Conversation. Confidential. Drafted by
                            <persName>Dulles</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                                type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1957-05-28">May 28,
                                1957</date>
                        </hi>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">MEMORANDUM OF CONVERSATION WITH SENATOR KNOWLAND AT THE GERMAN
                    EMBASSY</p>
                <p>I said to Knowland that we had concluded that there was no practical alternative
                    to allowing the Japanese to go ahead and exercise jurisdiction in the Girard
                    case. I pointed out that this had already been agreed to and I saw no practical
                    way of retracting our steps without throwing doubt upon the value of our
                    agreements and raising a storm which might sweep us out of all the Western
                    Pacific. Knowland said that would be “tough” but he did not indicate either
                    approval or disapproval.</p>
                <p>I talked in a like manner to Senator Alex Smith<note n="2" xml:id="d163fn2">
                        <persName>H. Alexander Smith</persName> of New Jersey, a member of the
                        Senate <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi> Committee.</note> and to
                    Congressmen <persName corresp="#p_GG1">GORDON</persName>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d163fn3">Thomas S. Gordon of Illinois, Chairman of the House
                        Committee on Foreign Affairs.</note> and Chiperfield.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d163fn4">
                        <persName>Robert B. Chiperfield</persName> of Illinois, ranking minority
                        member of the House Committee on Foreign Affairs.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">JFD</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
